\subsubsection{Reduction to a Pell equation}

Define
\[
X = 2C + 3^7, \qquad Y = 2B + 3^8.
\]
Then
\begin{align}
X^2 - 3Y^2 = 78 \cdot 3^{12}.
\end{align}

Write
\[
X = 3^6 \cdot x, \qquad Y = 3^6 \cdot y.
\]
Dividing through by $3^{12}$ yields the Pell-type equation
\begin{align}
x^2 - 3y^2 = 78
\end{align}

***********************************************************************

Considering the formulas in the table above, the proposed closed form solution to $A,B,C,D$ is:

\begin{align*}
    A_m &= \frac{-2 \cdot 3^{m+1} + 3^m \cdot \left[(15 - 7\sqrt{3})\cdot(7 - 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1} + (15 + 7\sqrt{3}) \cdot (7 + 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1}\right]}{4} + 3^{m+1} \\
    D_m &= \frac{-2 \cdot 3^{m+2} + 3^{m} \cdot \left[(7 - 5\sqrt{3})\cdot(7 - 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1} + (7 + 5\sqrt{3}) \cdot (7 + 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1}\right]}{4} + 3^{m+2} \\
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
    B_m = \frac{-2 \cdot 3^{m+2} + 3^{m} \cdot \left[(7 - 5\sqrt{3})\cdot(7 - 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1} + (7 + 5\sqrt{3}) \cdot (7 + 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1}\right]}{4}
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
    C_m = \frac{ -2 \cdot 3^{m+1} + 3^m \cdot \left[(15 -7\sqrt{3})\cdot(7 - 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1} + (15 + 7\sqrt{3}) \cdot (7 + 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1}\right]}{4}
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
    D_m = \frac{-2 \cdot 3^{m+2} + 3^{m} \cdot \left[(7 - 5\sqrt{3})\cdot(7 - 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1} + (7 + 5\sqrt{3}) \cdot (7 + 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1}\right]}{4} + 3^{m+2}
\end{align*}

***********************************************************************(correcting a draft section 3.2)

The Pell equation
 \begin{equation*}
        x^2 - 3y^2 = 1
    \end{equation*}
    has fundamental solution \((x_1, y_1) = (7, 4)\), since \(7^2 - 3(4)^2 = 1\).
    All solutions of the homogeneous Pell equation are generated by
    \[
        x + y\sqrt{3} = (7 + 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1}.
    \]

    Now, we seek a particular integer solution to \eqref{eq:pell}.
    Testing small integer values of $y$,
    \[
        y = 7 \quad \Rightarrow \quad x^2 = 78 + 3(7)^2 = 78 + 147 = 225 = 15^2.
    \]
    Hence, one particular solution is \((x_0, y_0) = (15, 7)\).

    The general integer solution to~\eqref{eq:pell} is therefore
    \[
        x + y\sqrt{3} = (15 + 7\sqrt{3})(7 + 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1}, \quad n \in \mathbb{Z}.
    \]
    Taking the conjugate and adding/subtracting, we obtain
    \begin{align*}
        x &= \frac{(15 + 7\sqrt{3})(7 + 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1} + (15 - 7\sqrt{3})(7 - 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1}}{2},\\[4pt]
        y &= \frac{(15 + 7\sqrt{3})(7 + 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1} - (15 - 7\sqrt{3})(7 - 4\sqrt{3})^{c_1}}{2\sqrt{3}}.
    \end{align*}

***********************************************************************(correcting a draft section 3.3)

\subsubsection{Reduction to a Pell equation}

